    <h2>Group A: Attempt any three questions.</h2><h3>Question 1</h3>
<div><p><p>Define system of linear equations. When a system of equations is consistent? Make echelon form to solve:</p>
<p>-2a – 3b + 4c = 5</p>
<p>b – 2c = 4</p>
<p>a + 3b – c = 2</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>A system of linear equations is a collection of one or more linear equations involving one or more variables. Each equation in the system is a linear combination of the variables, and the goal is to find values for the variables that satisfy all the equations simultaneously. In general, a system of linear equations can be represented as follows:</p>
<p>a₁x₁ + a₂x₂ + a₃x₃ + &#8230; + aₙxₙ = b₁<br />
a₁&#8217;x₁ + a₂&#8217;x₂ + a₃&#8217;x₃ + &#8230; + aₙ&#8217;xₙ = b₂<br />
a₁&#8221;x₁ + a₂&#8221;x₂ + a₃&#8221;x₃ + &#8230; + aₙ&#8221;xₙ = b₃<br />
&#8230;<br />
a₁ᵤx₁ + a₂ᵤx₂ + a₃ᵤx₃ + &#8230; + aₙᵤxₙ = bᵤ</p>
<p>Where:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>x₁, x₂, x₃, &#8230;, xₙ are the variables.</li>
<li>a₁, a₂, a₃, &#8230;, aₙ are the coefficients of the variables in the first equation.</li>
<li>b₁ is the constant on the right side of the first equation.</li>
<li>Similarly, a₁&#8217;, a₂&#8217;, a₃&#8217;, &#8230;, aₙ&#8217;, b₂, a₁&#8221;, a₂&#8221;, a₃&#8221;, &#8230;, aₙ&#8221;, b₃, and so on represent the coefficients and constants in the subsequent equations.</li>
</ul>
<p>A system of linear equations is consistent when it has at least one solution, which means there is a set of values for the variables that satisfies all the equations in the system. In other words, a system of equations is consistent if there is at least one combination of values for the variables that makes all the equations true simultaneously.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-25432" src="https://hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/SmartSelect_20230926_120552_CamScanner.jpg" alt="" width="1023" height="1705"></p>
</div>
<h3>Question 2</h3>
<div><p><p>Define linear transformation with an example.</p>
<p>Let A =<img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone  wp-image-25437" src="https://hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/a.jpg" alt="" width="83" height="80"> , v =<img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone  wp-image-25438" src="https://hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/v.jpg" alt="" width="48" height="57"> , b=<img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone  wp-image-25439" src="https://hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/b.jpg" alt="" width="59" height="75"> , x =<img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone  wp-image-25440" src="https://hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/x.jpg" alt="" width="41" height="55">,</p>
<p>and define a transformation T : R² → R² by T(x) = Ax then</p>
<p>a. find T(v).</p>
<p>b. Find x ∈ R² whose image under T is b.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>A linear transformation, in the context of linear algebra, is a function that maps vectors from one vector space to another in a way that preserves certain algebraic properties. Specifically, a linear transformation satisfies two fundamental properties:</p>
<p><strong>1. Additivity</strong>: If you apply the transformation to the sum of two vectors, it&#8217;s the same as applying the transformation to each vector separately and then adding the results. Mathematically, for vectors <code>v</code> and <code>w</code> and a linear transformation <code>T</code>, this property can be written as:</p>
<p>T(v + w) = T(v) + T(w)</p>
<p><strong>2. Scalar Multiplication</strong>: If you scale a vector and then apply the transformation, it&#8217;s the same as first applying the transformation and then scaling the result. Mathematically, for a scalar <code>c</code> and a vector <code>v</code>, this property can be written as:</p>
<p>T(c * v) = c * T(v)</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-25441" src="https://hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/SmartSelect_20230926_123930_CamScanner.jpg" alt="" width="1023" height="1835"></p>
</div>
<h3>Question 3</h3>
<div><p><p>Find AB by block multiplication of the matrices.</p>
<p>A=<img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone wp-image-25444" src="https://hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/a-1.jpg" alt="" width="153" height="71"> B=<img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone wp-image-25445" src="https://hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/b-1.jpg" alt="" width="67" height="98"></p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Given matrices:</p>
<p>$$<br />
A = \begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; -3 &amp; 1 \\ 0 &amp; -4 &amp; -2 \\ 1 &amp; -5 &amp; -2 \\ 0 &amp; 3 &amp; 7 \\ -4 &amp; -1 &amp; -1 \end{bmatrix}, \quad B = \begin{bmatrix} 6 &amp; 4 \\ 2 &amp; -1 \\ -3 &amp; 7 \\ 1 &amp; 3 \\ 5 &amp; -3 \end{bmatrix}<br />
$$</p>
<p>We partition the matrices as:</p>
<p>$$<br />
A = \begin{bmatrix} A_{11} &amp; A_{12} \\ A_{21} &amp; A_{22} \end{bmatrix}, \quad B = \begin{bmatrix} B_1 \\ B_2 \end{bmatrix}<br />
$$</p>
<p>Where:</p>
<p>$$<br />
A_{11} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; -3 \\ 1 &amp; -5 \\ 1 &amp; -2 \end{bmatrix}, \quad A_{12} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 &amp; -4 \\ 3 &amp; -1 \end{bmatrix}, \quad A_{21} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 &amp; -4 \\ -2 \end{bmatrix}, \quad A_{22} = \begin{bmatrix} 7 &amp; -1 \end{bmatrix}<br />
$$<br />
$$<br />
B_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 6 &amp; 4 \\ 2 &amp; -1 \\ -3 &amp; 7 \end{bmatrix}, \quad B_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; 5 \\ 3 &amp; -3 \end{bmatrix}<br />
$$</p>
<p>The formula for matrix multiplication is:</p>
<p>$$<br />
AB = \begin{bmatrix} A_{11} B_1 + A_{12} B_2 \\ A_{21} B_1 + A_{22} B_2 \end{bmatrix}$$</p>
<p>Step 1: Compute each block</p>
<p>$$<br />
A_{11} B_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 2(6) + (-3)(2) + 1(-3) \\ 2(4) + (-3)(-1) + 1(7) \\ 1(6) + (-5)(2) + (-2)(-3) \\ 1(4) + (-5)(-1) + (-2)(7) \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 18 \\ 2 \\ -5 \end{bmatrix}<br />
$$</p>
<p>$$<br />
A_{12} B_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 0(1) + (-4)(5) \\ 0(3) + (-4)(-3) \\ 3(1) + (-1)(5) \\ 3(3) + (-1)(-3) \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -20 \\ 12 \\ -2 \\ 12 \end{bmatrix}<br />
$$</p>
<p>$$<br />
A_{21} B_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 0(6) + (-4)(2) + (-2)(-3) \\ 0(4) + (-4)(-1) + (-2)(7) \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -2 \\ -10 \end{bmatrix}<br />
$$</p>
<p>$$<br />
A_{22} B_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 7(1) + (-1)(5) \\ 7(3) + (-1)(-3) \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 24 \end{bmatrix}<br />
$$</p>
<p>Step 2: Add the results</p>
<p>$$<br />
A_{11} B_1 + A_{12} B_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 18 \\ 2 \\ -5 \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} -20 \\ 12 \\ -2 \\ 12 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -17 \\ 30 \\ 0 \\ 7 \end{bmatrix}<br />
$$</p>
<p>$$<br />
A_{21} B_1 + A_{22} B_2 = \begin{bmatrix} -2 \\ -10 \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 24 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 14 \end{bmatrix}<br />
$$</p>
<p>Thus, the final result of matrix multiplication is:</p>
<p>$$<br />
AB = \begin{bmatrix} -17 &amp; 30 \\ 0 &amp; 7 \\ 0 &amp; 14 \end{bmatrix}<br />
$$</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
