<h3>Question 14</h3>
<div><p><p>Define group. Show that the set of integers is a group with respect to addition operation.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>A group is a fundamental algebraic structure in abstract algebra that consists of a set together with an operation that combines elements from the set and satisfies four key properties:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li><strong>Closure</strong>: For any two elements, a and b, in the group, their combination under the group operation must also be in the group. In other words, a * b is an element of the group.</li>
<li><strong>Associativity</strong>: The group operation is associative, which means that for any three elements a, b, and c in the group, the following equality holds: (a * b) * c = a * (b * c).</li>
<li><strong>Identity Element</strong>: There exists an identity element, denoted as &#8220;e&#8221; or &#8220;1,&#8221; such that for any element &#8220;a&#8221; in the group, the following equation is true: a * e = e * a = a.</li>
<li><strong>Inverse Element</strong>: For each element &#8220;a&#8221; in the group, there exists an inverse element &#8220;b&#8221; such that a * b = b * a = e, where &#8220;e&#8221; is the identity element.</li>
</ol>
<p>Now, let&#8217;s demonstrate that the set of integers, denoted as Z, forms a group with respect to the addition operation (+):</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li><strong>Closure</strong>: For any two integers &#8220;a&#8221; and &#8220;b,&#8221; their sum &#8220;a + b&#8221; is also an integer. Therefore, closure is satisfied.</li>
<li><strong>Associativity</strong>: Addition of integers is associative, meaning that for any integers &#8220;a,&#8221; &#8220;b,&#8221; and &#8220;c,&#8221; we have (a + b) + c = a + (b + c). This property holds.</li>
<li><strong>Identity Element</strong>: The identity element for addition in the set of integers is &#8220;0.&#8221; For any integer &#8220;a,&#8221; we have a + 0 = 0 + a = a. Therefore, the identity element is present.</li>
<li><strong>Inverse Element</strong>: For every integer &#8220;a,&#8221; its inverse with respect to addition is the negative of itself, denoted as &#8220;-a.&#8221; This means that a + (-a) = (-a) + a = 0. Thus, every integer has an inverse element.</li>
</ol>
<p>Since the set of integers satisfies all four properties of a group with respect to addition, it is indeed a group under addition. This group is known as the additive group of integers, often denoted as (Z, +), where &#8220;Z&#8221; represents the set of integers, and &#8220;+&#8221; represents the addition operation.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 15</h3>
<div><p><div class="group w-full text-token-text-primary border-b border-black/10 gizmo:border-0 dark:border-gray-900/50 gizmo:dark:border-0 gizmo:bg-transparent dark:bg-gray-800 gizmo:dark:bg-transparent" data-testid="conversation-turn-12">
<div class="p-4 justify-center text-base md:gap-6 md:py-6 m-auto">
<div class="flex flex-1 gap-4 text-base mx-auto md:gap-6 md:max-w-2xl lg:max-w-[38rem] xl:max-w-3xl }">
<div class="relative flex w-[calc(100%-50px)] flex-col gap-1 md:gap-3 lg:w-[calc(100%-115px)]">
<div class="flex flex-grow flex-col gap-3 max-w-full">
<div class="min-h-[20px] flex flex-col items-start gap-3 overflow-x-auto whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">
<div class="empty:hidden">Define ring and show that set of positive integers with respect to addition and multiplication operation is not a ring.</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>A ring is an algebraic structure in abstract algebra that consists of a set together with two binary operations: addition and multiplication. To be considered a ring, the following conditions must be satisfied:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li><strong>Closure under Addition</strong>: For any two elements &#8220;a&#8221; and &#8220;b&#8221; in the ring, their sum &#8220;a + b&#8221; must also be in the ring.</li>
<li><strong>Associativity of Addition</strong>: Addition in the ring must be associative, meaning that for any elements &#8220;a,&#8221; &#8220;b,&#8221; and &#8220;c&#8221; in the ring, the equation (a + b) + c = a + (b + c) holds.</li>
<li><strong>Existence of an Additive Identity</strong>: There exists an additive identity element, denoted as &#8220;0&#8221; (zero), such that for any element &#8220;a&#8221; in the ring, the equation a + 0 = 0 + a = a holds.</li>
<li><strong>Existence of Additive Inverses</strong>: For each element &#8220;a&#8221; in the ring, there exists an additive inverse element, denoted as &#8220;-a,&#8221; such that a + (-a) = (-a) + a = 0.</li>
<li><strong>Closure under Multiplication</strong>: For any two elements &#8220;a&#8221; and &#8220;b&#8221; in the ring, their product &#8220;a * b&#8221; must also be in the ring.</li>
<li><strong>Associativity of Multiplication</strong>: Multiplication in the ring must be associative, meaning that for any elements &#8220;a,&#8221; &#8220;b,&#8221; and &#8220;c&#8221; in the ring, the equation (a * b) * c = a * (b * c) holds.</li>
</ol>
<p>Now, let&#8217;s examine the set of positive integers, denoted as <strong>N+</strong>, and determine whether it forms a ring with respect to addition and multiplication:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li><strong>Closure under Addition</strong>: The set of positive integers is closed under addition. If you add two positive integers, the result is also a positive integer.</li>
<li><strong>Associativity of Addition</strong>: Addition of positive integers is associative. This property holds.</li>
<li><strong>Existence of an Additive Identity</strong>: The set of positive integers does not contain an additive identity &#8220;0&#8221; because it starts from 1 and does not include zero. Therefore, this property is not satisfied.</li>
<li><strong>Existence of Additive Inverses</strong>: The set of positive integers does not contain additive inverses. For any positive integer &#8220;a,&#8221; there is no positive integer &#8220;-a&#8221; such that a + (-a) = 0 because negative integers are not included. Therefore, this property is not satisfied.</li>
<li><strong>Closure under Multiplication</strong>: The set of positive integers is closed under multiplication. If you multiply two positive integers, the result is also a positive integer.</li>
<li><strong>Associativity of Multiplication</strong>: Multiplication of positive integers is associative. This property holds.</li>
</ol>
<p>Since the set of positive integers does not satisfy the properties of having an additive identity and additive inverses, it does not form a ring with respect to addition and multiplication. Therefore, the set of positive integers is not a ring; it is an example of a semiring.</p>
